{"title_page": "Edward Charles Bowra", "text_new": "[[File:Edward Charles Bowra (1870).jpeg|thumb|right|Edward Charles Bowra, circa 1870. The child is possibly his daughter Ethel.]]\n'''Edward Charles MacIntosh Bowra''' (1841\u20131874) was a British citizen serving in the [[Chinese Maritime Customs]] working for the government of the [[Qing dynasty]]. He was among those [[treaty port]] residents who contributed to Western knowledge of China through translations and scientific work.\n\n==Career==\nAs an amateur [[Sinologist]] and [[botanist]] he showed a range of scholarly and practical interests which reflected the then [[Orientalism|common view]] that a cultivated gentleman could master Oriental culture. He published a history of the province of [[Canton Province|Canton]],<ref>E. C. Bowra  ''The China Magazine'' (Hong Kong: Noronha & Sons, 1868\u20131870)</ref> and compiled ''Index Sinice et Latine'' for [[Justus Doolittle]]'s [https://books.google.com/books?id=KTsOAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=Bowra&f=false ''Vocabulary and Handbook of the Chinese Language''] (1872),<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=thmPzIltAV8C&pg=PA92 ''Dictionary of British and Irish botanists and horticulturists'']</ref> but his most widely known accomplishment was a pioneering translation of the first eight chapters of [[Dream of the Red Chamber]] in 1868.<ref>University of Virginia Chinese Text Initiative (This etext contains only the Preface and Chapter 1) {{cite web |url=http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/chinese |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111014065444/http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/chinese/ |archivedate=2011-10-14 }}</ref>\n\nBowra was educated at the [[City of London College]],  then served in the [[London]] [[Custom House, City of London|Custom House]] before he went to [[Italy]] to join the British Legion in support of [[Redshirts (Italy)|Red Shirts]] of [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] in their campaign for Italian unity.{{When|date=November 2011}}{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\n==Service in China==\nIn 1863 he was appointed clerk in the [[Chinese Maritime Customs]], serving under Sir [[Sir Robert Hart, 1st Baronet|Robert Hart]] in Tientsin and Shanghai. He was sent in 1864 as a [[student interpreter]] to Peking, then appointed interpreter in Canton. Bowra organised the 1866 tour for the Chinese Secretary of Customs, [[Pin Chun]]. In England Bowra married Thirza Woodward. On his return to China he was sent to [[Ningbo]], where his children Ethel and Cecil were born. He was promoted to Deputy Commissioner in 1872.He organized the Chinese contribution for the Vienna Exhibition of 1873, for which the Austrian government awarded him the Order of the Iron Crown.Bowra died in England at the age of thirty-two in 1874,<ref>\"Administrative/Biographical history,\" Bowra Papers, Archives in London [http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/vcdf/detail?coll_id=86&inst_id=19]</ref> apparently after over-exerting himself at a garden party. He was buried in the [[Catacombs of London|catacombs]] of [[West Norwood Cemetery]].\n\nHis son, Cecil Arthur Verner Bowra (1869\u20131947) also served in the Chinese Maritime Service.<ref>\"Administrative/Biographical history,\" Bowra Papers, Archives in London [http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/vcdf/detail?coll_id=86&inst_id=19]</ref> His grandson, [[Maurice Bowra]], born in [[Kiukiang]], became a prominent classical scholar.<ref>{{Cite web| last = Mitchell | first = Leslie | authorlink = Leslie Mitchell (historian)| year=2004 | title= Bowra, Sir (Cecil) Maurice (1898\u20131971) | work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography | url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/30841 | accessdate=2011-10-11}}</ref>\n\n==Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Charles Drage, ''Servants of the Dragon Throne: Being the Lives of Edward and Cecil Bowra'' (London: Peter Dawnay,  1966).\n\n== External links ==\n* Photograph [http://www.vcea.net/Digital_Library/Images_en.php?ID=26383 Bowra's Farewell Tiffin]\n* The Bowra Papers (of Edward Charles Bowra and Cecil Arthur Verner Bowra) are held by [https://www.soas.ac.uk/library/archives/collections/a-z/b/ SOAS Archives]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bowra, Edward Charles}}\n[[Category:1841 births]]\n[[Category:1874 deaths]]\n[[Category:British sinologists]]\n[[Category:Burials at West Norwood Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Edward Charles Bowra (1870).jpeg|thumb|right|Edward Charles Bowra, circa 1870. The child is possibly his daughter Ethel.]]\n'''Edward Charles MacIntosh Bowra''' (1841\u20131874) was a British citizen serving in the [[Chinese Maritime Customs]] working for the government of the [[Qing dynasty]]. He was among those [[treaty port]] residents who contributed to Western knowledge of China through translations and scientific work.\n\n==Career==\nAs an amateur [[Sinologist]] and [[botanist]] he showed a range of scholarly and practical interests which reflected the then [[Orientalism|common view]] that a cultivated gentleman could master Oriental culture. He published a history of the province of [[Canton Province|Canton]],<ref>E. C. Bowra  ''The China Magazine'' (Hong Kong: Noronha & Sons, 1868\u20131870)</ref> and compiled ''Index Sinice et Latine'' for [[Justus Doolittle]]'s [https://books.google.com/books?id=KTsOAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=Bowra&f=false ''Vocabulary and Handbook of the Chinese Language''] (1872),<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=thmPzIltAV8C&pg=PA92 ''Dictionary of British and Irish botanists and horticulturists'']</ref> but his most widely known accomplishment was a pioneering translation of the first eight chapters of [[Dream of the Red Chamber]] in 1868.<ref>University of Virginia Chinese Text Initiative (This etext contains only the Preface and Chapter 1) {{cite web |url=http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/chinese |title=Archived copy |accessdate=